'''Oral candidiasis''' (also known as '''oral candidosis''', '''(oral) thrush'''<ref name="Andrews">{{cite book |author=James, William D.; Berger, Timothy G.; et al. |title=Andrews' Diseases of the Skin: Clinical Dermatology |publisher=Saunders Elsevier |location= |year=2006 |pages= |isbn=0-7216-2921-0 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref>{{rp|308}} '''oropharyngeal candidiasis''', '''moniliasis'''<ref name="OMF medicine textbook">{{cite book|last=Scully|first=Crispian|title=Oral and maxillofacial medicine : the basis of diagnosis and treatment|year=2008|publisher=Churchill Livingstone|location=Edinburgh|isbn=9780443068188|edition=2nd ed.|pages=191–199}}</ref> '''candidal stomatitis''') is a common [[opportunistic infection|opportunistic]] [[mycosis]] (yeast infection) of [[Candida (genus)|Candida]] species on the [[mucous membrane]]s of the [[mouth]].

==Classification==
Being a type of [[candidiasis]], oral candidiasis is a [[mycosis]]. Traditionally, oral candidiasis is classified into acute and chronic forms (see table). The fact that rarely, some of the subtupes may present as either acute or chonic creates problems with this system.

